# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: al-nichols
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:al-nichols/1875-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:al-nichols/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:al-nichols/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:al-nichols/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:al-nichols/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:al-nichols/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:al-nichols/1877-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1877 throughout the world.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:al-nichols/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] Nichols got his start at third base for the 1875 Brooklyn Atlantics of the National Association.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] He batted only .153 in 32 games played that season.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] The following year, after the collapse of the Association, he played for the New York Mutuals of the new National League and didn't fare much better, hitting .179 in 57 games.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] It was for the Louisville Grays in 1877 that he would gain infamy.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] It was determined that he was involved in throwing games for money along with teammates George Hall, Jim Devlin, and Bill Craver.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] As a personal friend of Hall, he was brought in to play third base at Hall's insistence to replace Bill Hauge when he had to take time off due to injury.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] At this point, Louisville was in first place, but soon after Nichols' arrival, the team began to lose games at an alarming rate.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] Chase started to become suspicious when Nichols was still playing even though he continued to make key errors when Hauge was well enough to return to his starting position.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] His suspicion was confirmed when he received a couple telegrams instructing him to watch his players.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] Chase confronted the players, and Hall and Devlin confessed.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] The matter was referred to National League president William Hulbert, and Nichols was formally banned from Major League Baseball on December 4, 1877.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] Nichols came to the United States from England in 1861.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] After his banishment from baseball, he spent most of his life in the Brooklyn, New York area, got married and raised a family.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] He worked at various jobs, including as a shipping clerk and inspector, and was very remorseful about his role in the scandal, making many unsuccessful attempts to earn reinstatement.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] He died in Richmond Hill, New York, at the age of 84.
[src:al-nichols/al-nichols] He was cremated and interred at Green-Wood Cemetery in Brooklyn.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:al-nichols/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:al-nichols/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Before his baseball career, Craver had served in the military during the Civil War with the 13th Heavy Artillery Regiment out of New York.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He enlisted on January 21, 1864, as a Private in Company K, and mustered out on June 28 in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] When the war, and his military career were over, he began his organized baseball career as a catcher in 1866 with the Union Baseball Club of Rensselaer County, which became the Unions of Lansingburgh.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] The Unions gained the nickname of Haymakers in August of that year after a visit to the Capitoline Grounds and the Elysian Fields.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Later, in 1870, while playing for a Chicago team, he was accused of breaking his contract with the team.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] In 1871, Craver joined the Troy Haymakers, who entered the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in the league's first season.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He played second base, and after just four games, he replaced Lip Pike as manager.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He played well, batting .322, but the team finished in seventh place.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] For the next two seasons, he joined the Baltimore Canaries, the first of which he was player-manager.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He was replaced at manager later in the year by Everett Mills, but stayed with the team through the 1873 season.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Playing for the Philadelphia White Stockings in 1874, he led the league in games played, and as a second baseman, he led the league in putouts and errors.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Craver had his best offensive season that year, batting .343 and leading the league in stolen bases.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] In 1875, he moved over the Philadelphia Centennials.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He played in just 13 games for them when, together with George Bechtel, he was traded to the Philadelphia Athletics to replace injured players Dave Eggler and Wes Fisler in exchange for $1,500.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He led the NA in triples in 1875 with 13.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] The National Association folded following the 1875 season, and Craver joined the 1876 New York Mutuals, a team that he also managed.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] It was his only season in New York, as the Mutuals were expelled from the league for not making the required western trip.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] It was during this season that Craver was reputedly savagely beaten by a gambler for doublecrossing him on a fix.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He gained infamy the following season, his final season, when playing for the Louisville Grays.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] In 1877, the Grays were ahead in the league standings, with a 27–13 record with only 15 games left to play, but then lost their lead through horrible play, losing eight straight games at one point.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] The trouble reportedly began when third baseman Bill Hague was injured and needed to be replaced.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] George Hall suggested that the team pick up his former Mutuals teammate Al Nichols.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] The errors by Nichols, Hall, and Craver began to accumulate, and owner Charles Chase became suspicious when he noticed that Nichols was still in the lineup, even though Hague was fully healthy.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] The players were soon seen around town with new clothes and jewelry.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Chase confronted pitcher Jim Devlin and did not receive a confession, but Hall thought Devlin had confessed.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Hall claimed that Nichols was the person in contact with the gamblers and all three had thrown games.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Chase requested from each member of the team permission to see all the Western Union telegrams sent and received.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Craver was the only man on the team to refuse, which caused him to be suspended.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] The telegrams proved the three were in open communication with the gamblers.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] After his forced retirement from baseball, Craver became a police officer, along with fellow "criminal" Devlin.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] He began to receive military disability on July 1, 1892, as a result of time as a soldier, which would continue on to his widow, Catherine C.
[src:al-nichols/bill-craver] Craver died at the age of 57 of heart disease in his hometown of Troy, and is interred at Oakwood Cemetery.
